<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="59" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1167,1353]" box="[264,389,1167,1192]" pageId="2" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis box="[264,389,1167,1192]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="59">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,1167,1353]" pageId="2" pageNumber="59">
From 
<emphasis box="[382,441,1207,1232]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="59">Oryx</emphasis>
, the generic name of the gemsbok, which in itself is derived from the Latin (and Greek), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pape" authorityYear="2006" box="[419,471,1247,1272]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Hoplacephala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oryx">
<emphasis box="[419,471,1247,1272]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="59">oryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= pick or pick­axe. The species epithet is a noun in apposition and refers to the elongate pair of frontal setae, which may be reminiscent or at least suggestive of the long, slender horns of the gemsbok, with which the present species shares its habitat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
